MTV looking for a few unique souls

‘ RICK NEFF.
Staff Writer

They came in droves.

Black, white, preppy, punk, bald
and bleached — they arrived search-
ing for their 15 minutes of fame and a
chance to cavort naked in a hot tub on

a cable television.

Saturday afternoon, Bunim—

Murray, the production company

responsible for MTV’s hit shows
“The Real World” and “Road Rules,”
took over Rock Jungle at Station
Square to hold auditions for “Real
World: Las Vegas” and “Road Rules
11.”

After 10 on-air seasons, the
granddaddy of reality television
showed no sign of declining popular-
ity. The auditions were held between
10 a.m. and 5 p.m., but some people
claimed to have been in line since 1
a.m. Friday.

By 10 a.m., Rock Jungle’s park-
ing lot was the hippest place in
Pittsburgh. Gray skies and a chilly
breeze couldn’t stop the line that
stretched the length of the building
and around two red and black dump-
sters. Women wearing tiny skirts with

' knee-high boots huddled together to

stay warm, while swaying to the

  

 
  

 

  

 

music that was being played by a

Chevy Blazer with “105.9 The X”

painted on the side.

No one pushed and shoved, but
bouncers guarded the doors as they
let people slowly trickle into the
empty club. Throughout the day, the
line did not shrink. More and more
18- to 24-year-olds stepped out of
their cars and into the back of the
line. Those who finally stepped inside
were shocked to see that they were
only halfway through the wait. There
the line“, wove past the piranha tanks,
slithered past the pythons and con-
strictors before ending behind the
faux waterfalls.

Auditioners were given applica-

tions to ﬁll out that included ques-

tions such as, “What is your most
embarrassing moment?” and “How do
you approach a relationship?”

At the end of the line, “The Real
World” wannabes were greeted by
Mike, a cast member of “The Real
World: New York.” With boy band
looks and a friendly smile, women
screamed his name and ran up to hug
him.

Pitt Juniors Monika Puranik and
Sara Burton waited in line for nearly
four hours, but said that seeing Mike
helped. Both students are fans of the

show and try to watch every episode.

“When I saw him, I was freakin’
out,” Burton said.

When people reached the end of
the line, they sat at a table 12 at a time
for their interviews. The interviewing
process was done in one of three
round-table discussion groups.

At one table, Morgan Fahey con-
ducted the mass interview. Fahey is
the supervising casting director for
“The Real World.” Arniable and out-

going, she appears to harbor a love

for the show.
Fahey’ gushed about how people
should watch the just completed

' “Real World: Chicago” in January.

When pressed for details, all she
would say is that it is the first house
with both a Jacuzzi and a doublehead-
ed shower. ‘

“Look for the best ‘Too Hot for
TV’ Real World tapes,” she said.
J Still, sex ddesn’t always sell — at
least not in the interviewing process.

One group of auditioners includ-
ed a gorgeous woman who claimed to
have a large porn collection. She tried
to dominate the entire discussion
group by professing her love for all
things pornographic. -

In between talking about ho
much pot they smoke, almost every-

one else in the group agreed that porn
was “just great.” One girl disagreed.

She called pornography degrad-
ing to women.

Every one around her seemed
shocked at the suggestion. Still, the
girl held her ground. When the inter-
view was over, Fahey liked her the
best.

Fahey explained that most people 

auditioning try to put on a show. They
talk about how much drugs they do or
how much sex they have. Most of it
isn’t true, she said.

“We like people who -» are both
interesting and sincere, I felt that the
girl who had such strong /views
against pornography wasn’t putting
on an act and was the most interesting
person of that group,” she said.

By 3230 p.m. more than 800 peo-
ple auditioned. The bouncers let
another 100 into the club then locked
the doors. -As the line inside dwindled
down, the bouncers cleaned up the
signs on the walls and grabbed a beer.
Fahey said she would make the deci-
sion about who to call back later that
night.

When asked about their chances
for being picked for the show,
Puranik and Burton chanted in unison
“slim to none.”

  

