Agnihotri, who was chancellor
of the Southern University Law
School, said /that the offer of a posi-
tion as an ambassador came as a
surprise to him, since he had worked
in the United States for more than
25 years. He said that, as an Indian,
he felt ‘a close tie to the ‘United

States.

“We have similar experiences
that America has,” he said, pointing
out that democracy, free elections
and “freedom of spirit,” are charac-
teristics common to both countries.
These similarities, he said, made
Sept. 11 — which he called “the
most tragic experience of my life”
-— even harder on the Indian com-
munity. ’

“We as Indians were doubly
pained,” Agnihotri said.

Joining him as a speaker was
county executive Jim Roddey, who
recounted his experience on Sept.
11.

An emotional Roddey recalled
the phone call during which he
heard that a hijacked plane was 10
minutes outside of Pittsburgh, and
his reaction to the idea that it was
his choice whether to evacuate the
larger buildings in the city.

