EDITORIAL

Council should passliving wage

Today the Allegheny County Council
can make progress by voting to implement
a living wage — $9.12 per hour with bene-
ﬁts and $10.62 per hour without — for
employees of the county, its contractors
and businesses that receive Allegheny
County economic development assis-
tance.

The bill garnered its share of contro-
versy during the last several months. Both
sides of the struggle showered the Council
with statistics supporting their respective
positions. But as the Pittsburgh Post-
Gazette reported yesterday, little is proven
about its effect either way.

Allegheny County should try it from a
standpoint of fairness, if nothing else.

Imagine that you work 40 hours per
week, 51 weeks per year at the current
minimum wage of $5.15 per hour. Based
on our calculations, you would earn
$10,506 in a year — before deductions for
taxes, Social Security and Medicare.

It’s hard to survive on $10, 506 a year
as a single person. According to the U.S.
Department of Health and Human
Services (www.hhs.gov), the poverty line
for a single person household is $8,590.

It’s even harder if you have a family.
Health and Human Services calculate the
poverty line for a family of four at
$17,650.

Imagine having to work all year and
still being unable to make ends meet.
Based on 2000 Census data, which can be

found at www.census. gov, that’s how 12.5
percent of the population in this developed
country lives.

That’s how the living wage can help.
It varies for different areas of the country
depending on the cost of living. It is cal-
culated based on the amount of hourly
income it takes to support a family of four
at or above the poverty line for that area,
according to the Living Wage Campaign.

Opponents of this idea charge it will
cause inﬂation, force governments to raise
taxes and hurt the economy. But the dol-
lar’s strength rests on the strength of the
global economy. Its value would likely not
be affected. _

As those against President George W.
Bush’s tax cut plan noted, those at the bot-
tom of the economic scale tend to spend
more. Our economy is based on consump-
tion. So it stands to reason that putting
more money into the hands of those more
likely to spend it will boost the economy.

One can also argue that a living wage
will increase the quality of services ren-
dered, because it could cause more com-
petition for jobs and thus give workers
more incentive to perform to their best
capability. . V

Today, the Allegheny County Council
can take a stand against poverty. While no
one knows how it will work out, it is well
worth the uy. Doing something to combat
recession and poverty, as the New Deal
showed us, is betterthan nothing at all.

